LIBCFTEXT
=========

A lightweight, pure C library to determine whether a file contains text or
binary data.

OVERVIEW
--------

libcftext provides a single straightforward function, is_text_file(), that
reads the raw bytes of a file and applies a heuristic based on:

  - Absence of null bytes (0x00)
  - Proportion of non-printable characters

The library is written in standard C (C89/C99), has no external dependencies,
and can be compiled on any platform with a C compiler.  It exposes a minimal
public API that includes error reporting and version information.

FEATURES
--------

  * Single-function detection – call is_text_file() and get a clear answer.
  * No dependencies – relies only on the C standard library.
  * Portable – works on Linux, macOS, Windows, and other systems.
  * Binary safe – uses "rb" mode to avoid text-mode translations.
  * Configurable – the detection threshold can be changed via a build-time
    macro.
  * Informative errors – error codes and human-readable strings are provided.
  * Versioning – compile-time version macros and a runtime version function.
  * C++ compatible – wrapped in extern "C" for seamless use in C++ projects.

GETTING STARTED
---------------

Prerequisites:
  - A C compiler (GCC, Clang, MSVC, etc.)
  - GNU Make (or compatible) for the provided Makefile
  - Standard POSIX tools (ar, install) for building and installing

Building from Source:

  git clone https://github.com/mroczect/libcftext.git
  cd libcftext
  make

This produces:
  - libcftext.a   – static library
  - libftext      – example command-line tool

Object files are placed in the build/ directory and are ignored by Git.

Available Make targets:

  all       Build the library and the example tool (default)
  clean     Remove all build artifacts
  install   Install the library and header to /usr/local
  uninstall Remove installed files from /usr/local

Override the compiler or flags:

  make CC=clang CFLAGS="-O3 -march=native"

The install target respects DESTDIR for staged installations:

  make DESTDIR=/tmp/staging install

Linking Against the Library:

After building, include the header and link with -lcftext.

  #include "libcftext.h"

  int main(void) {
      int result = is_text_file("example.txt");
      if (result == 1) {
          /* text */
      }
      return 0;
  }

Compile and link:

  gcc -I./include myapp.c -L. -lcftext -o myapp

USAGE
-----

Command-Line Tool:

The included example program (libftext) can be used to test files directly.

  ./libftext document.txt

Output:
  text

If the file is binary:
  binary

On error:
  Error: Cannot open file

API REFERENCE
-------------

is_text_file()

  int is_text_file(const char *filename);

  Determines whether a file is text or binary.

  Parameters:
    filename – null-terminated path to the file. Must not be NULL.

  Returns:
    1  – file appears to be text (or is empty)
    0  – file appears to be binary
    -1 – an error occurred; retrieve the error with libcftext_get_error()

  Algorithm details:
    1. The file is opened in binary mode to avoid any platform-specific
       translations.
    2. Blocks of 4096 bytes are read sequentially.
    3. If a null byte (0x00) is encountered, the file is immediately
       classified as binary.
    4. Each byte is checked against a set of acceptable characters:
       printable ASCII (32-126), tab, newline, carriage return, and all
       high-bytes (>=128, which are considered part of multi-byte encodings
       like UTF-8).
    5. After reading, the percentage of bytes that are not in the acceptable
       set is calculated. If it exceeds 10%, the file is classified as
       binary. Otherwise, it is considered text.
    6. An empty file (0 bytes) is always classified as text.

  The 10% threshold can be adjusted by changing the MAX_NONPRINTABLE_PERCENT
  macro in src/core.c and recompiling.

  Thread safety: This function is not thread-safe because it modifies a
  global error state. In multithreaded applications, serialise access to
  is_text_file() and the related error functions, or ensure only one thread
  uses the library at a time.

Error Handling Functions

  int libcftext_get_error(void);
  void libcftext_set_error(int err);      /* internal use */
  const char *libcftext_strerror(int err);

  When is_text_file() returns -1, call libcftext_get_error() to obtain an
  error code, and libcftext_strerror() to get a human-readable description.

  Error codes:
    LIBCFTEXT_OK          (0)  No error
    LIBCFTEXT_ERR_NULL_PTR(1)  Filename argument was NULL
    LIBCFTEXT_ERR_OPEN    (2)  File could not be opened
    LIBCFTEXT_ERR_READ    (3)  Read error while processing file
    LIBCFTEXT_ERR_UNKNOWN (99) Unknown error (reserved)

  Example:
    int res = is_text_file("nonexistent.txt");
    if (res == -1) {
        int err = libcftext_get_error();
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed: %s\n", libcftext_strerror(err));
    }

  Note: libcftext_set_error() is used internally by the library to record
  the cause of an error. User code should not call it directly.

Version Information

  const char *libcftext_version(void);

  Returns a static string like "1.0.7".

  Compile-time version macros are also available in libcftext.h:
    LIBCFTEXT_VERSION_MAJOR
    LIBCFTEXT_VERSION_MINOR
    LIBCFTEXT_VERSION_PATCH
    LIBCFTEXT_VERSION       (full string)

PROJECT STRUCTURE
-----------------

  libcftext/
  ├── include/
  │   └── libcftext.h      # Public header
  ├── src/
  │   ├── core.c           # Detection logic
  │   ├── error.c          # Error state and messages
  │   └── version.c        # Version function
  ├── main.c               # Command-line example
  ├── Makefile             # Build automation
  ├── .gitignore
  └── README

VERSIONING
----------

This project follows Semantic Versioning (https://semver.org). The current
version is 1.0.7.

